comment: For this and other O forms, there is a form Keen calls O1 (object of a transitive clause, p. 213), and a second she calls O2 (object of a semi-transitive clause). There are many conditions under which O will be a distinct form rather than equal to A and S – basically whenever an 'antipassive' applies. However, the form given here is the most basic, according to Keen's description
